^B@2^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|The terms upgradeable and downgradeable have nothing to do with whether or not the hand contains a lot of formal HCP.  Upgradeable simply means that the true value is greater than the formal number of HCP.|

ht|c|at|^B@2Example 3:|HT|d|at|^c|ih|pS 5 4 3   H A T 9 8 7   D K T 9 8 7   C|
ht|i|va|6|at|^B@2Example 3 is a very upgradeable hand. It only has 7 formal HCP. But it has great ^*Bdistribution^*N and attractive ^*Blong suits^*N with lovely ^*Bspot cards^*N. The true value of this hand is significantly greater than 7.|
PG| ***** 3 ***** |


ht|c|at|^lExample 4: |HT|d|at|^m|ih|pS Q J 2   H Q J 3 2   D K Q J   C  Q J 2|

ht|l|at|^B@2On the other hand, Example 4 is very downgradeable. It contains a lot of honor cards and 15 formal HCP. But with no ^*Baces or intermediate cards, no fewer than 8 quacks, and the worst possible distribution^*N, its true value is far less than 15. If you think that I would not ever consider opening a 15-17 1NT with this pile of garbage, you are 100% correct.|
PG| ***** 4 ***** |


ht|p|at|^B@2Example 5: |hT|p|at|^e|ih|pS A 8 6 5   H K 5 2   D J 9 4 3   C 6 3|

ht|p|AT|^M@2On the other hand, many hands are neither upgradeable nor downgradeable. I think of them as "OK as is". Example 5 falls in this category. It contains 8 formal HCP. There is no reason to upgrade or downgrade this modest hand.|
