qx|A2,|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|After forming a first impression, my next step is to count formal HCP just like a beginner would. Then comes the most important step. I adjust the formal point count to what I think is the hand's true value. I will demonstrate how I do that shortly.|
PG| ***** 8 ***** |


at|

Using 4-3-2-1 values to represent kings, queens, and jacks is not completely accurate. You need not memorize the following but it is worth mentioning:
* The true value of an ace is 4 1/2 points.
* A king is correct with its assigned value of 3 points.
* A queen is only worth 1 1/2 points.
* A jack is worth 3/4 of a point.
* A ten, like an ace, is an underrated honor. It is worth 1/4 of a point.|
PG| ***** 9 ***** |


at|

Without forcing students to use fractions and make counting high card points a complicated process, my practical method to rectify the imperfections of using the traditional values is to suggest the following:
* If your hand contains at least 3 aces or 3 tens, add one HCP.
* If your hand contains at least 3 queens or 3 jacks, subtract 1 HCP.|
PG| ***** 10 ***** |


ht|o|at|^B@2You should love being dealt aces. Those players who complain about hands with "aces and spaces", such as Example 9,|
ht|p|at|^B@2Example 9: |ht|p|at|^e|ih|pS A 6 5 4   H A 5 3   D 6 3   C A 6 3 2|
ht|p|at|^m@2are announcing their lack of understanding of what bridge is all about. It is nice to have picture cards along with your aces. But any time I get more than my share of aces, I am a very happy camper.|
PG| ***** 11 ***** |


 


ht|s|at|^m@2On the other hand, holding no aces is never good. Do I subtract a point for that? When there is nothing wrong with the hand I would not subtract although I am disappointed. But when I get a degradeable hand I definitely would make that formal subtraction.|
PG| ***** 12 ***** |


ht|w|AT|^b@2An expert friend told me a long time ago "It's uncanny how well hands work out when they contain no jacks." He was not saying he prefers holding a deuce to holding a jack. He was just saying that when you pick up a jack and add one point, that often does not accurately reflect the value of the hand. With too many hands, a jack turns out to be a worthless honor. But, obviously, a jack could also be a critical card. If you have a queen and a ten in a 4-card suit, you would be much happier if partner holds the jack rather than not. Every card has its day in the sun.|
