^B@2^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|The length of your suits matters. You should take it into account before the bidding starts. Look at Examples 17-20.


Example 17: @S K J 4 3   ^H@H 6 2   @D A 5 3   ^L@C K T 3 2
Example 18: @S K J 4 3 2   ^H@H 6 2   @D A 5    ^L@C K T 3 2
Example 19: @S K J 6 4 3 2   ^H@H 6 2   @D A 5   ^L@C K T 2
Example 20: @S K J 7 6 4 3 2   ^H@H 6 2   @D A 5  ^L@C K 10

All of these hands have the same high cards--11 HCP. Example 17 has no suit longer than four cards. Example 18 contains five spades.  Example 19 has six spades. Example 20 includes a 7-card spade suit.|
PG| ***** 15 ***** |


AT|

I hope you know that Hand 20 is the best of the group. Having a long suit is better than having no long suit, and the longer the better. Longer suits help you take more tricks. That's what bridge is all about. How much better are hands with long suits? Traditional thinking says add one point for each 5-card suit (in case you are lucky enough to have more than one). Add two points for a 6-card suit, 3 points for a 7-card suit, and so forth. That is sensible as soon as you pick up your hand.|
